{
  "section_id": "08-crossbar-limits",
  "title": "Crossbar Limits",
  "title_translation": "Crossbar架构的局限性",
  "paragraphs": [
    {
      "id": "p000",
      "index": 0,
      "source": "As designers tried to increase core counts further, they ran into scaling limits of these early interconnects. As minimal latency and uniformity was desired, crossbar designs were used in an all-to-all fashion, where every core has a discrete link to all other cores on die. However, the number of links increased greatly with more cores, increasing complexity.",
      "source_html": null,
      "element_type": "p",
      "inline_elements": [],
      "parent_block_id": "b0064",
      "parent_block_index": 64,
      "parent_block_type": "p",
      "parent_block_markdown": "As designers tried to increase core counts further, they ran into scaling limits of these early interconnects. As minimal latency and uniformity was desired, crossbar designs were used in an all-to-all fashion, where every core has a discrete link to all other cores on die. However, the number of links increased greatly with more cores, increasing complexity.",
      "parent_block_plain_text": "As designers tried to increase core counts further, they ran into scaling limits of these early interconnects. As minimal latency and uniformity was desired, crossbar designs were used in an all-to-all fashion, where every core has a discrete link to all other cores on die. However, the number of links increased greatly with more cores, increasing complexity.",
      "parent_source_html": null,
      "parent_inline_elements": [],
      "segment_start": 0,
      "segment_end": 361,
      "expected_tokens": [],
      "format_recovery_status": "not_applicable",
      "format_errors": [],
      "is_heading": false,
      "heading_level": null,
